Lab From A Chip is a DIY intervention in lab-on-a-chip technology inspired by science and technology studies (STS) and microbiological technique. It's part of Ross Dalziel's PhD research project, Critical Kits, at the Division for BioMedical Life Sciences at Lancaster University (BLS) and makerspace DoESLiverpool making add-ons for the Foldscope, a folding paper microscope by Prakash Labs.
"A lab-on-a-chip is a device that integrates one or several laboratory functions on a single integrated circuit of only millimeters to a few square centimeters" Wikipedia

It's a review of bio-technology & microbiological technique, the material practices of doing bio-science. We've packaged up the existing, friendly & cheap Foldscope; alongside the innovative practice of scientist and engineer Alexandre Benedetto and his colleagues at BLS.

They make cheap robust consistent PDMS microfluidic channels to watch nematode worms using old vinyl audio records as moulds. Our add-ons make the process accessible to DIY newcomers & lets you follow their practice using vinyl fragments, surplus electronics and Euglena gracilis, a light sensitive algae.
Lab From A Chip:
Foldscope Add-Ons

Now setup your phone with the Foldscope and see if our algal friends have found their way into our microfluidic channels. This can be tricky! The vinyl record technique is the most rewarding, you get to see our Euglena gracilis moving along the grooves; and understand their scale compared to yours. The chip surface is more subtle, but you can take slabs from the underside markings.
These organisms are mixotrophic in that they ingest food but also photosynthesise, so like plants 'make' food from sunlight and so respond to it.

Have a think what other ordinary stuff we have in our homes and workplaces that might have tiny spaces the size of record grooves or silicon chip logos? What about textiles or the surface of a battery or a splinter of wood? Once you put yourself in the Algae's position the human engineered world and all it's 'freedoms' becomes vast and almost terrifying in it's scale and impact yet easy to forget and make invisible. Think about what histories might have been necessary to make these spaces and indeed this kit possible. Share your images to Twitter and copy @CriticalKits and @PrakashLab or Instagram @cheapjack @foldscope

You can take part in the CriticalKits research project by reading and completing the Participant Information Sheet (PIS) included which explains the nature of the research. Sign, scan and email or ask questions to r.dalziel@lancaster.ac.uk
We'll contact you by email and explain how to participate and we'll keep your address confidential. All is explained in the PIS document. Happy intervening!
Standard Foldscoep classroom kit, instructions, cover slip stickers & paper slide set, lens cleaning Q-tip, lens stage.
Inject equal amounts (approx. 0.4ml) of silicon from syringe A and fixer from syringe B into the 'floor' your mini petri dish (it's the smaller diameter part)
Mix well and submerge your vinyl fragment in the floor of the petridish. Leave room for your chip. If it's not submerged add PDMS mix.
Get Moulding!

Bend back the pins of the 555 chip so they point up. You should be able to submerge the chip and the bent pins will stop it sinking to the very bottom of the dish to make sure you get a substantial 'slab' of PDMS. This is like the reverse of the vinyl technique.

Now we need to leave our mix to set overnight with the lid on. Think of other ways to make moulds; as long as you contain the edges of the mix, perhaps with a bottle top, it will set into a decent slab.
